1.1/ # of decisions made by private sector led sectorial council (end of project target: 10);
1.2/ # of decisions implemented by the sectorial councils (end of project target: 5);
1.3/ # of proposals initiated by farmers led extension boards;Up to 16 (end of project target: 5);
1.4/ # of farmers’ extension board decisions considered by A-VET providers (end of project target: 10);
2.1/ # of PPPs are active in A-VET and AE delivery (end of project target: 8);
2.2/ # of farmers and students are served by A-VET and AE institutions (end of project target: 12 000 farmers and 1850 students (30% female);
2.3/ # of operational Farmers’ Extension Boards (end of project target: 16);
3.1/ % increase in number of WBL graduates/year (end of project target: 10%);
3.2/ # of students/year gained access to improved vocational skills; (end of project target: 500 students/year (Youth 80%, Adults 20%, Female 30%));
3.3/ # of A-VET graduates employed in agricultural sector per year; (end of project target: 320 A-VET graduates (30% female) );
3.4/ # of extension client farmers applying improved agriculture practice per year.(end of project target: 3,460 extension client farmers (Youth 20%; Adults 80%; Female 20%));

Output:
1.1 Coordination mechanism for A-VET is strengthened with the stakeholders   
1.2 Coordination mechanism for Extension is identified and piloted with the stakeholders  
2.1 Public and private partners contribute to the provision of A-VET, including profile & curricula development, WBL implementation and examination.
2.2 Public and private partners are strengthened to contribute to the provision of farmer based extension services including short term training, counselling services, management advice, entrepreneurial support and other services.
